Added "type : nonSecure" option to generateUUID command. The type indicates the algorithm used for UUID generation. Unfortunately, the "secure" algorithm (which continues to be the default) can be comparatively slow - if it uses /dev/random on Linux, it can block waiting for sufficient entropy to build up. In contrast, the new "nonSecure" algorithm never blocks and is much faster. The "nonSecure" algorithm uses a secure random seed but is otherwise deterministic, though it is one of the [strongest uniform pseudo-random number generators known so far|http://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-math/javadocs/api-3.2/org/apache/commons/math3/random/Well19937c.html].

Fixed misc UI bugs, and hopefully also the strange exception I encountered earlier.

The latter may be a bug in the JRE:
http://bugs.sun.com/bugdatabase/view_bug.do?bug_id=7075600
I have sidestepped the problem by forcing java to use the old mergesort instead of the newer 'timsort' algorithm.
Mergesort is often slower, but this isn't really noticable on the client.

I have added it in MedSavantClient.Main with:
System.setProperty("java.util.Arrays.useLegacyMergeSort", "true");

This could also be set via a command line parameter, if that's preferrable.
-Djava.util.Arrays.useLegacyMergeSort=true

Since this change, I haven't received the exception.
